Chapter 1
Cohren
4:30 AM, Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently getting out of bed, he put on his combat uniform, wore his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pockets, he quietly exited the barracks, the sound of crushed mud and ice echoing under his boots.
He took a lighter from his vest pocket and a cigarette from the other. Lighting it, he took a small puff before gently opening the door. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake up the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm, half the time it didn't work, because all that came out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
"You're waking them up?" Cohren turned around to see Second Lieutenant Nemic approaching.
"Yeah," replied Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well, primo, we didn't want to see what you had planned for waking us up today. Secundo, the first shock troops up are the first at breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He extended his hand and flipped a switch. An alarm rang out inside the barracks, loud and shrieking. He heard noise inside and commotion.
"Damn it, Valturi," Nemic shouted. "You would think they would have learned to get up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did," Cohren turned to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their group and section leaders know how to get up before their units.
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out in mass. Everyone had what they needed, from personal items to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more annoyed.
"Good morning everyone," said Cohren in a cheerful voice.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you insist on waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troop members, a corporal.
"Because standard wake-ups are crap. And because Daybreak doesn't do the morning sleep-in," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As the first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to supervise and assist the company with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I give you and your units fifty minutes to complete final checks and get rations for the day."
The members of the Exodus company dispersed. They were part of the second division of shock troops, second army. Originally, they were split into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. It was a split company and Cohren didn't know what to think about his promotion to first lieutenant, mainly the reasons that had motivated it.
Cohren and Nemic, the commander of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the base's numerous floodlights, powered by generators. Most were painted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had used Wild Weasel attacks, both in the air and on the ground, to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," Nemic began with a dry laugh. "Where are we being sent?"
"An advanced operational base outside Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground assault," Cohren replied, taking a puff of his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for introducing him to tobacco, but a year of combat changes a man, and he kept quiet.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," Nemic muttered. "All the news coming from there is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan front.' Why not send help to the Howland front?"
"Amen, brother," Cohren said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "In any case, we're going with the first armored platoon, so we won't have to walk. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Did Shaw get us a transport?" Nemic asked, a bit surprised.
"Yeah. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "To all units of the Exodus company, meet at the west vehicle park when you're done. We're leaving with the first armored platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were all low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they arrived here. All four had been very close friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed so long ago, even though it couldn't have been more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith had been commanding the second platoon for a week now, after the previous commander was demobilized, injured by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked toward the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busy ensuring their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the armored platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked toward them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
